SQL-04
Employee Age Analysis
Easy
Table: employees (with date_of_birth column)
Problem
Calculate each employee's current age, then group them into age brackets (Under 25, 25–35, 35–50, 50+) and show the count per bracket.
Solution
-- Part 1: Calculate age and show per employee
SELECT
    name,
    date_of_birth,
    TIMESTAMPDIFF(YEAR, date_of_birth, CURDATE()) AS age,
    CASE
        WHEN TIMESTAMPDIFF(YEAR, date_of_birth, CURDATE()) < 25 THEN 'Under 25'
        WHEN TIMESTAMPDIFF(YEAR, date_of_birth, CURDATE()) < 35 THEN '25-35'
        WHEN TIMESTAMPDIFF(YEAR, date_of_birth, CURDATE()) < 50 THEN '35-50'
        ELSE '50+'
    END AS age_bracket
FROM employees;

-- Part 2: Count per age bracket
SELECT
    CASE
        WHEN TIMESTAMPDIFF(YEAR, date_of_birth, CURDATE()) < 25 THEN 'Under 25'
        WHEN TIMESTAMPDIFF(YEAR, date_of_birth, CURDATE()) < 35 THEN '25-35'
        WHEN TIMESTAMPDIFF(YEAR, date_of_birth, CURDATE()) < 50 THEN '35-50'
        ELSE '50+'
    END AS age_bracket,
    COUNT(*) AS employee_count
FROM employees
GROUP BY age_bracket
ORDER BY age_bracket;
Key functions: TIMESTAMPDIFF(YEAR, dob, CURDATE()) gives exact age in years. DATEDIFF() gives difference in days. CASE WHEN is the SQL equivalent of if-else — use it to create computed categorical columns. You can GROUP BY the CASE expression directly.